Linux Driver for Cisco Systems Inc. VIC Ethernet NIC
====================================================

Enic is the Linux driver for the Cisco Systems Inc. VIC Ethernet NIC.

See the KNOWN_ISSUES file for known issues with this release.

See the LICENSE file for license information.


Supported Platforms and Distributions
=====================================

The enic driver is supported on a variety of hardware platforms and
Linux distributions.  Please see the Cisco UCS Hardware Compatibility
List (HCL) for a list of compatible hardware and Linux distributions:

    https://ucshcltool.cloudapps.cisco.com/public/

Note that Cisco only tests the binary distribution of this driver
against GA releases of Linux distributions.  Meaning: if you upgrade
your Linux kernel beyond the kernel version from the GA version of
your Linux distribution, this driver may no longer work.

If you need to upgrade your kernel beyond the GA version, you may be
able to compile this driver from source, but that takes a bit more
knowledge and skill.

Finally, note that -- by default -- UEFI Secure Boot is only supported
with the binary driver packages distributed from cisco.com.  If you
compile this driver from source, it will not support UEFI Secure Boot
unless you sign the driver and add the appropriate validation into the
boot sequence.  See below for more information about UEFI Secure Boot.


Installation
============

The inbox enic driver in many Linux distributions is suitable for most
uses.  However, updated enic drivers may be available for download
from Cisco.com (in both binary and source code form).  These updated
enic drivers can be installed in several different ways:

1. Binary package (RPM)
2. Binary package (deb)
3. ISO image
4. Source code tarball

Instructions for each of these installation methods are described
below.  After the driver has been installed, you need to load it, and
then verify that it is running.  See instructions for each of these
steps below.


SLES Note
---------

SLES has inbox versions of both the Cisco enic Linux kernel driver and
the Cisco usNIC Linux kernel driver.  These two drivers are
interdependent upon each other; if you upgrade one, you must upgrade
both.  For example, if you only upgrade enic, the SLES kernel
dependency checker will determine that the new enic driver breaks the
inbox usNIC driver, and therefore it will ignore the new enic driver
(and use the inbox enic and usNIC drivers).

Each of the installation methods below will include a special note
about how to install both the enic and usNIC drivers on SLES.

This situation does not occur in other supported Linux distributions.


Install: Binary package (RPM)
-----------------------------

1) Verify that your running kernel matches one of the supported
distributions listed in the HCL.  For example, you can use the "uname
-r" command to see the version of your running kernel and verify it
against the kernel version in the RPM filename / metadata that you
wish to use.

If kernel version does not match, the enic RPM may not be able to be
installed.

2) Install the enic RPM (requires administrative privileges):

   Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL):
   # rpm -ihv kmod-enic-<version>-<release>.<distro>.x86_86.rpm

   SuSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES):
   # rpm -ivh cisco-enic-usnic-kmp-default-<version>-<release>.x86_64.rpm

   Note that the SLES RPMs are a "combo" RPM containing updated
   versions of both the enic and usNIC drivers.  Installing this RPM
   will upgrade *both* drivers simultaneously.

   XenServer:
   # rpm -ivh enic-<kernel_version>-modules-<version>-<release>.x86.rpm
   # rpm -ivh enic-debuginfo-<version>.x86.rpm
     (optional for debuginfo support)

   CentOS:
   # rpm -ihv kmod-enic-<version>-<release>.<distro>.x86_86.rpm

NOTE: If the install fails because a previous version of enic RPM was
      installed, use the rpm -Uhv <rpm_file_name> command to do an RPM
      update.

At this point the driver is installed but not loaded in the running
kernel.

The RPM can be uninstalled using the "-e" option (requires
administrative privileges):

   Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL):
   # rpm -e kmod-enic

   SuSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES):
   # rpm -e cisco-enic-usnic-kmp-default

   Xen Server:
   # rpm -e enic-<version>

NOTE: Be sure that you are not connected to the server via an enic
      interface, or your session will be severed.  You may wish to
      execute this command either on the console or in a KVM session,
      for example.


Install: Binary package (deb)
-----------------------------

1) Verify that your running kernel matches one of the supported
distributions listed in the HCL.  For example, you can use the "uname
-r" command to see the version of your running kernel and verify it
against the kernel version in the DEB filename / metadata that you
wish to use.

If kernel version does not match, the enic DEB may not be able to be
installed.

2) Install the enic DEB (requires administrative privileges):

   Ubuntu:
   # dpkg -i kmod-enic_<kernel_version>-<version>-<release>_amd64.deb

At this point the driver is installed but not loaded in the running
kernel.

The DEB can be uninstalled using the "-r" option (requires
administrative privileges):

   Ubuntu:
   # dpkg -r kmod-enic

NOTE: Be sure that you are not connected to the server via an enic
      interface, or your session will be severed.  You may wish to
      execute this command either on the console or in a KVM session,
      for example.


Install: ISO image
------------------

In some cases, it is useful to install an ISO 9660 CD-ROM file system
image during a Linux distribution installation in order to have the
most recent enic driver immediately upon first boot.

The driver ISO image must be built on a system with the same Linux
distribution and version as the target.

1) Prerequisites:
  1.1) Red Hat:
  The target build system must have createrepo RPM and kernel-*-devel
  RPMs installed.

  1.2) SLES:
  - The SLES driver disk build needs the SLES Linux RPMs (install
    DVD1) and SLES SDK to create the build system.

  - The SLES SDK can be downloaded from:
    http://developer.novell.com/wiki/index.php/SLES_SDK

  - The target build system must have the following RPMs installed:
    - build RPM (from SLES SDK)
    - kernel-*-devel RPMs

  - The default locations for RPMS as seen by the build scripts are:
    - SLES install DVD1 contents available under /media/dvd/sles
    - SLES install sdk contents available under /media/dvd/sles_sdk

  - Example Commands to loop mount the SLES ISOs:
    # mkdir -p /media/dvd/sles /media/dvd/sles_sdk
    # mount -o loop SLES-11-SP1-DVD-x86_64-GM-DVD1.iso /media/dvd/sles
    # mount -o loop SLE-11-SP1-SDK-DVD-x86_64-GM-DVD1.iso /media/dvd/sles_sdk

  - The above mentioned default locations can be overridden by setting the
    BUILD_RPMS environment variable. BUILD_RPMS must be set to locations of
    both SLES RPMS and SLES SDK.
    - Example (for bash):
    # export BUILD_RPMS=/media/dvd/mySuSE:/media/dvd/mySuSESDK

  1.3) XenServer:
  The target build system is a XenServer DDK (Driver Development Kit)
  VM that provides the necessary compile infrastructure to build
  driver disks or supplement packs. It is required to use a DDK VM
  that corresponds to the build of the XenServer that the drivers will
  be targeted at. This is the only way supported by Citrix for
  building drivers for XenServer.

  Process for setting up DDK VM:
  a) Obtain matching XenServer product and DDK build ISOs from
     http://citrix.com/English/ss/downloads/
  b) Install XenServer onto a host server.
  c) Install the XenCenter administrator console onto a Windows-based
     machine.
  d) Use XenCenter to import the DDK onto the XenServer host as a new
     virtual machine.

2) Extract the enic tarball and build driver disk image:

   $ tar xf enic-<version>.tar.bz2
   $ cd enic-<version>
   $ ./configure
   $ make package

3) The directory images/ contains enic-<version>-<release>-<distro>-dd.iso.

Once the ISO has been built, it can be installed one of two ways
during the Linux distribution installation:

1) Manual during distribution DVD install

  1.1) Red Hat: boot: prompt
  Boot from the OS DVD image and at the boot: prompt, enter linux dd
  Or for RHEL 6.x append dd to the kernel command line. This will prompt
  you for a driver disk.

  1.2) SLES:
  Boot from the OS DVD image and at the boot: prompt, enter
  driverupdate=1 at the bootoptions prompt or press F6 and choose "Yes".
  This will prompt you for a driver disk. The installer will
  load the driver fron the disk. Once done it will prompt you back
  for any additional driver disks. When done choose the "Back" button to
  proceed with installation.

  On all supported Linux distributions, the installer will use the
  driver from the driver disk during the install (if network
  connectivity is required), and will replace the built-in driver
  with the driver from the driver disk once the OS is installed.

  1.3) XenServer:
  Boot from the OS DVD image and at the boot: prompt, enter 'shell'.
  You will be presented with a command prompt. Enter 'rmmod enic' to
  remove the built-in driver. Enter 'exit' to return to installer.
  Press F9 key when prompted to provide the driver disk. Then proceed
  with the driver disk installation.

2) Manual during PXE/linux install

  2.1) Red Hat:
  By adding the dd to the kernel command line, the installer will
  prompt for a driver disk as in method 1). Add dd to the append line
  in the PXE/linux config file.  Here is an example PXE/linux config
  file:

     default rhel5_4
     prompt 1
     timeout 60

     label rhel5_4
     kernel /vmlinuz
     append initrd=/initrd.img dd

For all methods above, refer to the distribution documentation.

Once the Linux distribution finishes installing and reboots, the
updated enic driver should be loaded in the running kernel.


Install: Source code tarball
----------------------------

1) Extract the tarball and build/install the driver:

   $ tar xf enic-<version>.tar.bz2
   $ cd enic-<version>
   $ ./configure
   $ make

   # make install (requires administrative privileges)

2) After the driver is installed, re-create the boot loader with the
   new enic driver:

   SLES12:
       # mkinitrd --force -m enic
       (make initrd ramfs image with enic module)

       Note that SLES does not support third-party kernel modules by
       default. In order to enable the unsupported module, you need to
       add "allow_unsupported_modules 1" to
       /etc/modprobe.d/10-unsupported-modules.conf

       Note that you will also need to compile and install an updated
       Cisco usNIC driver as well.  The Cisco usNIC driver source code
       is part of the same UCS Drivers download as the enic sources.

   SLES11:
       # mkinitrd -m enic

   RHEL/CentOS 6.x, 7.x, XS:
       # mkinitrd <img file> <kernel version> --force --preload enic

       Example:
       # mkinitrd /boot/initramfs-3.10.0-123.el7.x86_64.img \
             3.10.0-123.el7.x86_64 --force --preload enic
   Ubuntu:
       # mkinitramfs -o /boot/initrd.img-`uname -r` `uname -r`

At this point the driver is installed but not loaded in the running
kernel.


Loading/unloading the enic driver
=================================

There are two ways to load the updated enic driver:

1. Automatically
2. Manually


Automatically loading the enic driver
-------------------------------------

If the enic driver was successfully installed, rebooting the server
should load it into the running kernel.  Even if your Linux
distribution has an older inbox version of the enic driver, the
newly-installed enic driver should take precedence.


Manually loading the enic driver
--------------------------------

Manually unloading a previous enic driver and loading a newer enic
driver is possible in some scenarios, but is not recommended.  For
example, SLES does not support rmmod'ing kernel modules from a running
kernel; SuSE recommends configuring modules in /etc/modprobe.d/ and
rebooting.

This procedure requires administrative privileges.

1) Unload the currently-running driver:

        # rmmod enic

NOTE: Ensure that you are not connected to the server where you are
      unloading the enic driver via an enic interface when you execute
      this command, or your connection will be severed.  You may wish
      to execute this command either on the console or in a KVM
      session, for example.

2) Load the updated driver:

You can load from the local build directory:

        # /sbin/insmod ./enic.ko

Or you can load from lib/modules if the driver was installed:

        # /sbin/modprobe enic

UEFI Secure Boot
----------------

The Linux binary kernel driver packages that are distributed by
cisco.com support UEFI Secure Boot.

Specifically, if UCS servers are booted in UEFI boot mode and have
Secure Boot enabled, the Linux kernel requires that all drivers must
be a) cryptographically signed and b) validated by a public key in the
Linux kernel keychain.

Secure Boot causes Cisco public cryptographic certificates to be
loaded from the UCS chassis hardware to the Linux kernel keychain.
The keys from these certificates will successfully validate genuine
Cisco drivers (e.g., those distributed from cisco.com).

If a driver's signature can be validated against the Cisco public
keys, the Linux kernel will allow the driver to load.  If a driver's
signature fails to validate, the Linux kernel will refuse to load it.

When *not* booting with Secure Boot, the Cisco cryptographic
certificates are *not* loaded in to the Linux kernel.  Hence, when the
Linux kernel loads a Cisco binary driver from cisco.com, a matching
public key will not be found that can validate the driver's signature.
You may see a warning like this:

  Request for unknown module key 'Cisco UCS Driver Signing REL Cert: ...'

However, since the server was not booted with Secure Boot, the Linux
kernel will load the driver anyway (even though it was unable to
validate the driver's cryptographic signature) -- the message is only
a warning.


Verify the version of the enic driver in the running kernel
===========================================================

After you have updated the enic driver and loaded it, you should
verify that the kernel is actually running the updated driver:

Check that a driver named "enic" is present in the running kernel:

        # /sbin/lsmod | grep enic

Then check the kernel log to see the version the enic driver the last
time it was loaded:

        # /bin/dmesg | grep enic

Check to ensure that the version is what you expect it to be.

Be sure to check the enic version from the *last* time it was loaded
in the kernel (e.g., dmesg may still show log messages from when the
prior enic driver was loaded).
